On this Sunday, though, Temi [tweeted](https://x.com/iamtemibabs/status/1733828139921383599) about [adapters](https://huggingface.co/papers/2106.09685)—small layers added to specific parts of a much larger neural network. The idea behind adapters was pretty genius. It solved a big problem with large model fine-tuning: you’d run out of memory if you tried to update the weights of the entire network. But with adapters, you freeze all the layers of the large model and only update the weights of the tiny adapter layers. This allowed fine-tuning on consumer GPUs and made it possible to use one model for a variety of different tasks—train multiple adapters and swap them on the fly. Some form of this adapter idea is even powering [Apple Intelligence](https://www.apple.com/apple-intelligence/) now.
